<article>
    <h1>10 ways to en&#xAD;able and em&#xAD;power</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20200919/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-09-19"><time>2020-09-19</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE | HOME AND GARDEN</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>The Lien Foun­da­tion’s Hack Care ini­tia­tive re­ferred to the ev­i­dence-based De­men­tia En­abling En­vi­ron­ment Prin­ci­ples devel­oped by Pro­fes­sor Richard Flem­ing and de­men­tia spe­cial­ist ar­chi­tect Kirsty Ben­nett from the Univer­sity of Wol­lon­gong in Aus­tralia in 2014.</p>
    <p>The prin­ci­ples be­low were drawn from the team’s de­sign and re­search ex­per­tise and per­sonal care­giv­ing ex­pe­ri­ence.</p>
    <p>1. Al­low an ac­tive role</p>
    <p>As much as pos­si­ble, help per­sons with de­men­tia do as many things by them­selves as they can.</p>
    <p>Do­ing so main­tains an ac­tive state of mind and helps slow down cog­ni­tive de­cline.</p>
    <p>2. En­cour­age de­ci­sion-mak­ing Present sim­ple choices and let per­sons with de­men­tia con­tinue to make their own de­ci­sions. This helps stim­u­late their minds and also gives them con­trol.</p>
    <p>3. Af­firm the sense of self Re­spect them as per­sons and hon­our their de­sires and pref­er­ences.</p>
    <p>4. Have sim­ple con­ve­niences within easy reach</p>
    <p>When they can ful­fil sim­ple needs by them­selves, their sense of be­ing in con­trol is re­in­forced. Bal­ance be­tween be­ing en­abling and pro­tec­tive.</p>
    <p>5. Fa­mil­iar­ity is com­fort­ing Avoid dras­tic changes. In­clude ha­bit­ual rit­u­als and ob­jects that re­as­sure as these help to con­jure fa­mil­iar as­so­ci­a­tions and mem­o­ries.</p>
    <p>6. Re­mem­ber sim­ple plea­sures De­light­ful sen­sa­tions, how­ever fleet­ing, can im­prove one’s spirit and well-be­ing.</p>
    <p>7. Sim­plify the en­vi­ron­ment Clut­ter, noise and other vis­ual stim­uli can be dis­ori­ent­ing. Re­move these en­vi­ron­men­tal trig­gers for calm­ness and seren­ity.</p>
    <p>8. Do things to­gether</p>
    <p>En­cour­age fam­ily mem­bers to in­ter­act mean­ing­fully with the fam­ily mem­ber with de­men­tia. In­clude him in ev­ery­day fam­ily ac­tiv­i­ties, but let him en­gage on his own terms.</p>
    <p>9. Stay flex­i­ble and adapt­able Car­ing re­quires ver­sa­til­ity to man­age un­ex­pected sit­u­a­tions. It helps to be or­gan­ised and pre­pared. Be will­ing to ask for help.</p>
    <p>10. The care­giver also mat­ters</p>
    <p>Sim­plify things for the care­giver as much as pos­si­ble and make time for reg­u­lar breaks. Self-care al­lows the care­giver to care for his or her loved one.</p>


</article>

